\title{Avalanches in Neural Networks}
\institute{Virginia Tech Department of Physics \& Center for Soft Matter and Biological Physics}
\author{Jacob Carroll, Ada Warren, \& Uwe T{\"a}uber}
\maketitle





\begin{columns}

  \column{.33}
  \block{Introduction \& Motivation}{

    \begin{itemize}
    \item  Neural networks are a class of dynamic models of the brain that have the ability to encode and store patterns of data, and later recognize them from partial or fragmented segments of this data.

      %%  This encoding and recognition of data also forms a model for how actual brains learn and store data[4], as well as how signals propagate throughout the brain[5].
      %% \\
    \item Signals that propagate through many neurons at once are called cascades or "avalanches" of neurons, and the frequency at which they occur is believed to be one of the factors responsible for memory. 
      
    \item These cascades or avalanches of neuronal firing, if occurring improperly or irregularly, can cause a variety of neurological conditions such as Parkinson's or seizures.

    \item Understanding the dynamics of these avalanches would provide insight into the inner workings of the brain.

      %% \item  Control of these avalanches via local stimulation of neuron potentials would provide a way to treat many of these neurological conditions. 

      %% \item  This has been experimentally realized to some degree in the case of treating Parkinson's with Deep Brain Stimulation, the activation of a small number of neurons in the brain[7].
    \end{itemize}

    
    %%  Neurons are the building blocks of brains and neurological matter. Idividually neurons are simple structures, but taken in in groups of interconected neurons the dynamics quickly outstretch  and form the basis for all ............................................................

    
    %%  The dynamics of these highly complex systems are poorly understood, and it is the goal of this research is to characterize and modify a proposed model of neural networks which reproduces some expermental results taken from real neuron activity, with the goal of control the activity of these networks.
    \vspace{1.1cm}

  }

  \column{.33}
  \block{Neurons}{
